research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0041.json:104:    "description": "Keep the active `gated` family and move to the optimizer axis now that the LR sweep has identified `2.0e-3` as the best current signum setting. Run `ARCHITECTURE=gated`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, and `LR=2.0e-3` with all reference aux/runtime knobs explicitly pinned, and change only `OPTIMIZER` from `signum` to `adam`. Judge the result by the whole trajectory, not just endpoint: if `adam` descends more cleanly or closes the gap at the stronger `2.0e-3` anchor, it earns exactly one LR callback next; if it is flatter, noisier, or clearly worse again, lock `signum` as the gated optimizer and stop the optimizer branch.",
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0017.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"On the updated best anchor `lowrank_two_stage_residual, K=32, EF=12, LR=3.2e-3`, introducing a small auxiliary loss with `AUXK_ALPHA=0.01` may improve feature utilization enough to reduce FVU further without changing sparsity cost.","summary":"Run an isolated aux sweep on the new best `K=32` recipe, holding architecture, K, expansion factor, optimizer, and LR fixed while changing only `AUXK_ALPHA` from `0.0` to `0.01`.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"lowrank_two_stage_residual","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This follows the current exploitation lane cleanly: only one parameter changes from the latest successful run, and the test stays on the strongest anchor rather than broadening search. After finding a better LR, the highest-information next step is a small aux value rather than another large recipe change.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_two_stage_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"32"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.01"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 17 should exploit the improved `K=32, EF=12` anchor by testing a small nonzero `AUXK_ALPHA=0.01` with all other fields pinned to the new best recipe.","This probes whether the stronger `LR=3.2e-3` optimization setting changes the aux tradeoff relative to the earlier low-K failures, which may have been regime-specific rather than family-wide."],"next_hypotheses":["If `AUXK_ALPHA=0.01` improves the `K=32` anchor, try `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0625` next on the same fixed recipe to map the local optimum.","If it is neutral or worse, revert to `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` for the high-quality anchor and consider the remaining LR sweep point only if more confirmation is needed.","If the gain is small but real, keep the new aux setting on the `K=32` anchor and then test whether the same setting transfers to a smaller-K frontier point."],"primary_variable":"auxk_alpha"}
research/history_archive/15_20260326_190606/logs/agent_action_0008.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"`K=96` established a valid smaller-support `topk` point without crashing, so the next single-question K-stage move is to measure whether the cost-quality slope stays acceptable when support is cut more materially. Dropping from `K=96` to `K=64` on the same tuned signum recipe will show whether LUTurbo can gain a more meaningful selection-cost reduction before reconstruction degrades too sharply.","summary":"Keep the `topk` mainline recipe fixed at `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, and `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125`, and change only `K` from `96` to `64`. This continues the K-stage mapping in the same family and answers one concrete question: whether the first nontrivial support cut beyond `K=96` still yields an acceptable Pareto tradeoff for deployment-oriented cost reduction.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"smaller_k","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This respects the single-variable rule and stays on the active family while extending the K frontier in the prescribed final stage. The main risk is that `K=64` may fall off the quality cliff, so the result should be judged by the whole curve and by whether the extra support reduction is large enough to justify any observed FVU loss.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"K","value":"64"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"2.0e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.03125"},{"key":"DEAD_FEATURE_THRESHOLD","value":"10000000"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"0"},{"key":"HOOKPOINTS","value":"layers.[3].self_attn.o_proj"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["`topk` now has two EF=12 frontier anchors under the tuned signum recipe: `K=128` at `FVU=0.4522051215171814` and `K=96` at `FVU=0.4886302351951599`.","Round 8 continues the K stage by testing `K=64` under the same `topk` signum recipe to estimate whether a larger support reduction can still be deployment-viable.","Interpret this round by both curve shape and Pareto value: even if FVU worsens, `K=64` may still matter if degradation is gradual rather than cliff-like."],"next_hypotheses":["If `K=64` remains reasonably close to the `K=96` point, continue to `K=32` on the same recipe to map the low-K slope.","If `K=64` shows a sharp quality cliff, stop forcing lower K on plain `topk` and treat new family search as the more promising route for LUTurbo cost reduction.","If `K=64` is borderline, compare its curve shape against `K=96` to decide whether the lower-K regime deserves an LR retune before abandoning it."],"primary_variable":"k"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0046.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"After hard failures from branch-mixing, thresholded sparsity, staged residual coding, and batch-level budget allocation, a discrete coarse-code baseline is the next fundamentally different mechanism worth testing: `residual_vq` at `K=24, EF=12` may recover a better mid-K tradeoff by handling shared structure with a learned codebook before sparse residual correction.","summary":"Run a pure architecture comparison at `K=24, EF=12` with `residual_vq` under the pinned recipe `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=3.2e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0`. This matches the severe-stagnation policy by continuing the search over genuinely different built-in families rather than any further scalar tweak.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"residual_vq","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"I avoided LR, aux, K, and EF sweeps because 11 no-improve rounds means minor tuning is exhausted. I also kept K fixed at 24 for a clean read against the current frontier slot while moving to a substantially different discrete-reconstruction family.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"residual_vq"},{"key":"K","value":"24"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 46 continues severe-stagnation recovery with a codebook-based family after `multi_branch_gated`, `jumprelu`, `two_stage_residual`, and `batch_topk` all failed badly at K=24.","Keep the run architecture-only at K=24, EF=12 with every recipe field pinned explicitly.","`residual_vq` tests a qualitatively different coarse-plus-residual mechanism than the recent continuous sparse-coding families."],"next_hypotheses":["If `residual_vq` is competitive but slightly worse at K=24, test `two_code_residual_vq` at the same K to see whether a deeper discrete coarse stage helps.","If `residual_vq` clearly loses at K=24, reject this codebook branch and move to another fundamentally different family such as `factorized_topk` rather than any scalar sweep.","If `residual_vq` wins at K=24, follow with K=16 or K=32 to map whether the gain generalizes across the mid-K band."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0081.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"`lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` now forms a smooth non-dominated low-K ladder at `K=9/10/12/16/24/32`, and the previous `K=8` miss only shows that it does not beat the same-K anchor. The highest-value next step is therefore a controlled `K=7` probe to see whether this family can add an even smaller non-dominated tradeoff point, which matters more than matching the `K=8` incumbent exactly.","summary":"Run one parameter-only experiment at `K=7` with `lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual`, keeping `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=3.2e-3`, and `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` fixed. This continues the downward sweep with one variable changed and tests whether the hybrid still yields a useful Pareto point below the current `K=8` anchor. Success means achieving FVU clearly below the current `K=4` frontier point (`0.14181029796600342`), which would create a new non-dominated `K=7` tradeoff even if it does not beat the `K=8` same-K incumbent.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"pareto_tradeoff","family_name":"lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"promote_to_mainline","self_review":"This is the most frontier-aligned next move: it prioritizes lower K rather than spending another round polishing the already-resolved `K=8` boundary. The recipe stays fixed, the hypothesis is singular, and the outcome is easy to interpret against the existing `K=8` and `K=4` anchors.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"7"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 81 should be a controlled parameter-only probe of `lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` at `K=7` after confirmed non-dominated points at `K=9` and above, plus a known same-K miss at `K=8`.","The success criterion is frontier expansion, not beating the `K=8` incumbent at the same K: if `K=7` lands below the `K=4` FVU anchor (`0.14181029796600342`), it is a valid new Pareto tradeoff under the fixed recipe."],"next_hypotheses":["If `K=7` yields a strong non-dominated point, test `K=6` to continue extending the low-K frontier.","If `K=7` is only marginally non-dominated, consider a confirmatory rerun before pushing lower.","If `K=7` clearly underperforms and approaches the `K=4` anchor, conclude this family's useful regime likely ends around `K=9` and shift future effort elsewhere."],"primary_variable":"k"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0083.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"`lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` remained smoothly non-dominated at `K=6` under the fixed recipe, so the next single-variable probe should reduce only `K` to `5` and test whether this family can extend the low-K Pareto frontier one step further before crossing the current `K=4` anchor.","summary":"Run one parameter-only experiment at `K=5` with `lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual`, keeping `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=3.2e-3`, and `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` fixed. Success criterion: add a new non-dominated point by landing below the current `K=4` frontier FVU (`0.14181029796600342`), with stronger evidence if it continues the smooth degradation trend from `K=7` (`0.12780356407165527`) to `K=6` (`0.13256755471229553`).","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"smaller_k","family_name":"lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This stays within the current strongest signal: one family, one fixed recipe, one variable. `K=6` was clearly non-dominated rather than a borderline near-miss, so advancing to `K=5` is a better use of the next round than a confirmatory rerun.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"5"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 83 should be a controlled parameter-only probe at `K=5` for `lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` after confirmed non-dominated points at `K=6` and above under the fixed `EF=12` / `signum` / `LR=3.2e-3` / `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` recipe.","The success criterion is frontier expansion rather than a same-K comparison: if `K=5` stays below the current `K=4` anchor FVU (`0.14181029796600342`), it is a valid new Pareto tradeoff."],"next_hypotheses":["If `K=5` yields another strong non-dominated point, test `K=4` in the same family to compare directly against the current `K=4` anchor.","If `K=5` is only marginally below the `K=4` anchor, do one confirmatory rerun at `K=5` before pushing lower.","If `K=5` misses the `K=4` anchor clearly, conclude this family's useful low-K frontier likely ends at `K=6` and shift exploration to a new family or mechanism."],"primary_variable":"k"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/memory.json:1525:      "design_hypothesis": "After three distinct K32 soft-codebook backbones failed to beat the bucketed point under `EF=16`, the next severe-stagnation step should continue architecture search only along an already-registered but mechanistically different branch rather than return to scalar tweaks. `lowrank_gated_soft_codebook_residual` is the strongest remaining soft-codebook variant by prior results and may yield a better small-K tradeoff at `K=32, EF=16` by using learned gating instead of bucket partitioning or hard routing.",
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0014.json:20:    "summary": "Run a single loss-axis test on the existing topk mainline: keep `ARCHITECTURE=topk`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, and `LR=1.6e-3` fixed, and lower `AUXK_ALPHA` to `0.015625` to see whether the current recipe is over-regularized.",
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0014.json:29:        "key": "ARCHITECTURE",
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0014.json:82:    "description": "Run a single loss-axis test on the existing topk mainline: keep `ARCHITECTURE=topk`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, and `LR=1.6e-3` fixed, and lower `AUXK_ALPHA` to `0.015625` to see whether the current recipe is over-regularized.",
research/history_archive/15_20260326_190606/logs/agent_action_0007.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The optimizer and aux-loss stages did not improve on the `topk` signum anchor, so the next mainline question is whether a slightly smaller support can preserve most of the reconstruction while improving LUTurbo deployment cost. Reducing `K` from `128` to `96` is the least aggressive first step on the K axis and should reveal whether the current topk recipe has obvious over-allocation in support size.","summary":"Keep the `topk` mainline recipe fixed at `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, and the original auxiliary setting, and change only `K` from `128` to `96`. This starts the K stage with the nearest lower allowed value, so the run cleanly answers whether LUTurbo can gain a cost-friendly support reduction before quality drops sharply.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"smaller_k","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This follows the prescribed order: LR and optimizer were explored, the aux-loss probe did not improve the frontier, and now the search moves to K. The main risk is that `K=96` may be too close to `K=128` to unlock a meaningful deployment gain, but it is still the most interpretable first K move and gives a clean slope estimate for the cost-quality tradeoff.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"K","value":"96"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"2.0e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.03125"},{"key":"DEAD_FEATURE_THRESHOLD","value":"10000000"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"0"},{"key":"HOOKPOINTS","value":"layers.[3].self_attn.o_proj"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["`topk` remains the active mainline family, with the current best EF=12 anchor at `K=128`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `FVU=0.4522051215171814`.","The `adam` optimizer probe regressed and the aux-loss removal probe failed to improve, so the next justified mainline step is the K stage.","Round 7 begins K exploration with the smallest possible move from the anchor, `K=96`, to estimate the local cost-quality slope before taking larger support cuts."],"next_hypotheses":["If `K=96` stays close to the `K=128` anchor with a healthy curve, continue down to `K=64` on the same recipe to look for a real LUTurbo cost win.","If `K=96` regresses sharply, treat the current topk recipe as support-hungry and consider whether a new family is needed rather than forcing smaller K.","If `K=96` is mixed, compare curve shape and late slope to decide whether the degradation is true capacity loss or a sign that the lower-K regime needs its own LR retune."],"primary_variable":"k"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0164.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"After repeated failures from residual-only, routed, and bucketed residual variants at `K=24, EF=16`, the next severe-stagnation move should still be a fundamentally different existing architecture rather than another recipe tweak. `lowrank_soft_codebook_residual` is the most informative next candidate because it tests whether a simpler single-stage soft-codebook composition can recover a better small-K tradeoff than the recently exhausted two-stage, routed, bucketed, and plain residual paths under the fixed modern signum recipe.","summary":"Run an architecture-only comparison at `K=24, EF=16` by switching to `lowrank_soft_codebook_residual` while keeping optimizer, LR, aux loss, and preprocessing fixed at the current signum baseline. This continues severe-stagnation recovery with a materially different existing family, targets the valuable `K=24` frontier slot, and checks whether single-stage soft-codebook composition works better than the more structured variants that have recently failed.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"pareto_tradeoff","family_name":"lowrank_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This is a clean single-variable architecture probe and is more defensible than returning to optimizer or preprocessing after many misses. The main risk is that the broader soft-codebook family has already looked weaker than the bucketed winner, but the simpler one-stage variant has not been given a direct modern `K=24, EF=16` comparison and remains structurally different enough to justify one controlled test.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_soft_codebook_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"24"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 164 continues severe-stagnation architecture search after bucketed low-rank residual also failed to improve the `K=24, EF=16` lane.","Hypothesis: `lowrank_soft_codebook_residual` is the next materially different existing family because single-stage soft-codebook composition may scale down more gracefully at `K=24` than the recently exhausted two-stage, routed, bucketed, and plain residual variants under the fixed signum recipe."],"next_hypotheses":["If `lowrank_soft_codebook_residual` is competitive at `K=24`, follow with `K=16` on the same family to test whether the simpler codebook composition extends further down the frontier.","If it is close but still behind the bucketed soft-codebook backbone, test another fundamentally different existing family at `K=24` rather than returning to scalar recipe tweaks.","If it clearly loses at `K=24`, deprioritize plain single-stage soft-codebook residual coding in the current EF=16 regime and continue severe-stagnation search with the next distinct architecture."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0020.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Now that `routed_lowrank_two_stage_residual` is integrated, an architecture-only run at `K=16, EF=12` can test whether router-guided support selection improves the mid-low-K frontier over the current `lowrank_two_stage_residual` point (`FVU=0.10792168974876404`) without changing optimization or width.","summary":"Round 19 was rejected on isolation grounds before producing a training result, so the clean follow-up is to execute the already-integrated family as a pure architecture comparison. Run `routed_lowrank_two_stage_residual` at `K=16, EF=12` with the established low-K signum recipe and no code changes this round.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"routed_lowrank_two_stage_residual","family_stage":"incubating","self_review":"This fixes the previous policy issue by removing code edits from the round and keeping the experiment to a single primary variable: architecture. The main risk is that the routed variant may need router-strength calibration, but the first priority is obtaining a valid comparable datapoint at the target frontier slot.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"routed_lowrank_two_stage_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"16"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 19 was policy-rejected before execution because code-edit introduction and architecture change were coupled; treat the family as already integrated and schedule a pure architecture-only run next.","Use the exact low-K baseline recipe when evaluating `routed_lowrank_two_stage_residual` so the comparison against the current `K=16, EF=12` frontier point is clean."],"next_hypotheses":["If `routed_lowrank_two_stage_residual` wins at `K=16`, run the same family at `K=24, EF=12` to test transfer along the adjacent frontier slot.","If it is close but worse than baseline, keep the family alive and test a smaller routing perturbation in a later code round.","If it clearly loses at `K=16`, return to `lowrank_two_stage_residual` and resume smaller-K frontier work there."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0031.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"After five rounds without improvement and with the low-K lane already mapped across `K in {1,2,4,8,16,24,32}`, the next step should be a fundamentally different architecture rather than another minor tweak. `routed_lowrank_two_stage_residual` may outperform the current `lowrank_two_stage_residual` baseline in the mid-low-K regime when tested as a clean architecture-only swap at `K=16` under the settled recipe.","summary":"Run a pure architecture comparison at `K=16, EF=12` by switching from `lowrank_two_stage_residual` to `routed_lowrank_two_stage_residual` while keeping optimizer, learning rate, and aux fixed to the current best-controlled low-K recipe.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"fvu","family_name":"routed_lowrank_two_stage_residual","family_stage":"incubating","self_review":"This follows the severe-stagnation policy directly: K coverage is already broad, so the next move must be a fundamentally different architecture. `K=16` is the cleanest comparison point because the routed family was previously identified as a plausible mid-K contender, and holding `EF=12`, `signum`, `LR=3.2e-3`, and `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` fixed isolates architecture as the only primary variable.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"routed_lowrank_two_stage_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"16"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 31 exits minor-tweak exploitation due to severe stagnation and tests a fundamentally different family: `routed_lowrank_two_stage_residual` at `K=16, EF=12` under the exact settled low-K recipe for a clean architecture-only comparison."],"next_hypotheses":["If `routed_lowrank_two_stage_residual` wins at `K=16`, continue the same architecture-only comparison at `K=24` under the same recipe.","If it is close but slightly worse, keep the family incubating and test it at `K=24` before rejecting it.","If it clearly loses at `K=16`, return to `lowrank_two_stage_residual` and open a different substantial branch rather than more minor sweeps."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0093.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The routed soft-codebook two-stage family has now improved both `K=8` and `K=16`, so the next highest-value test is whether the same routing advantage extends to `K=24`, where the current frontier is still owned by the non-routed variant.","summary":"Run one parameter-only follow-up at `K=24` with `routed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual`, keeping `EF=12`, `signum`, `LR=3.2e-3`, and `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` fixed. This cleanly maps whether the new family is becoming the dominant low/mid-K backbone rather than a narrow win at only `K=8` and `K=16`.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"frontier_improve","family_name":"routed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"active","self_review":"This is a straightforward exploitation step with a single changed dimension (`K`). It directly follows the observed frontier gains and avoids unnecessary code churn. The main risk is that routing helps only in tighter-budget regimes and may become neutral or harmful by `K=24`, but that is precisely what this run will resolve.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"routed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"24"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["r93 should extend the routed soft-codebook family sweep to `K=24` after frontier wins at `K=8` and `K=16`.","Keep the recipe fixed and change only `K` so the result cleanly measures whether routing remains helpful in the mid-K regime.","A `K=24` win would strongly suggest the routed soft-codebook family is the new EF=12 backbone across multiple frontier slots."],"next_hypotheses":["If `routed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` wins at `K=24`, test it at `K=32` under the same recipe to see whether routing can displace the current high end of the EF=12 frontier as well.","If it is close but slightly behind at `K=24`, consider a small routed-temperature adjustment as the first targeted tuning step for this family.","If it clearly loses at `K=24`, conclude that the routed advantage likely tops out by `K=16` and focus future routed-family work on low-K slots only."],"primary_variable":"k"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0056.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"After 20 no-improve rounds and repeated failures from routed, gated, discrete, bucketed, and low-rank variants at `K=24`, the next severe-stagnation move should reset to the simplest fundamentally different baseline rather than layering on more mechanism. Plain `topk` at `K=24, EF=12` may outperform the recent complex branches by avoiding their optimization overhead and support-allocation pathologies, potentially recovering a cleaner mid-K Pareto point.","summary":"Run a pure architecture comparison at `K=24, EF=12` with `topk` under the pinned recipe `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=3.2e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0`. This follows severe-stagnation policy by making an architecture-only jump away from the recent failed mechanisms and re-establishing whether the plain sparse-coding baseline is stronger than the accumulated complex alternatives at the frontier-relevant mid-K slot.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"baseline_recheck","self_review":"I avoided more support-selection or low-rank refinements because policy says minor tweaks are exhausted, and the recent complex families all lost badly at `K=24`. Rechecking plain `topk` is a defensible fundamentally different move: it strips away auxiliary architectural assumptions and gives a clean reference point under the same pinned recipe.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"K","value":"24"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 56 continues severe-stagnation recovery by resetting to plain `topk` at `K=24` after multiple more complex families failed badly in the same slot.","Keep the run pinned at `K=24, EF=12, signum, LR=3.2e-3, AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` so architecture is the only primary variable.","`topk` tests whether the mid-K frontier is better served by the simplest sparse coding baseline than by the recent routed, gated, bucketed, discrete, and low-rank mechanisms."],"next_hypotheses":["If `topk` is competitive but slightly worse at K=24, test it at K=16 to see whether the simpler baseline is stronger under tighter sparsity.","If `topk` clearly loses at K=24, retire the plain-baseline reset and move to another genuinely different built-in family rather than any scalar sweep.","If `topk` wins at K=24, follow with K=16 or K=32 to map whether the simpler architecture generalizes across the mid-K band."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/15_20260326_190606/logs/agent_action_0002.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The exact clean baseline is not executable in this controller because `no_change` actions are policy-rejected, so the least-deviating Round 2 move is a single-variable `topk` learning-rate probe around the reference recipe. A modest LR increase from `8e-4` to `1.2e-3` may improve convergence speed and end-of-run FVU at `K=128` without changing the family, optimizer, or LUTurbo compatibility path.","summary":"Keep the mainline `topk` family and the full reference recipe fixed, changing only `LR` from `8e-4` to `1.2e-3` at `K=128, EXPANSION_FACTOR=12, OPTIMIZER=signum`. This is the smallest policy-valid follow-up after the rejected clean-baseline attempt and should answer one concrete question: whether the current signum topk anchor is mildly under-stepped.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This stays on the same family, respects the single-variable rule, and follows the recommended search order as closely as the controller allows after rejecting `no_change`. The main risk is that we still lack a true baseline curve, so interpretation must compare curve shape against the reference recipe expectation rather than against an actual completed `LR=8e-4` run.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.03125"},{"key":"DEAD_FEATURE_THRESHOLD","value":"10000000"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"0"},{"key":"HOOKPOINTS","value":"layers.[3].self_attn.o_proj"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["The controller rejects exact clean-baseline submissions when encoded as `no_change`, so mainline progress must proceed through a policy-valid single-axis variant.","Round 2 keeps `topk` fixed and starts the recommended LR stage with a modest upward step from the reference `8e-4` recipe.","Judge this run by curve shape as well as final FVU: smoother early descent with continued late improvement would support staying on the higher-LR branch."],"next_hypotheses":["If `LR=1.2e-3` gives a smoother or better curve, try one more upward LR step on the same `topk` recipe before changing optimizer.","If the curve becomes noisy or degrades late, step down below the reference LR on the same family and optimizer.","If LR tuning looks exhausted without a clear gain, keep `topk` fixed and move to the next optimizer as the next single-variable question."],"primary_variable":"lr"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0042.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Under severe stagnation, switch from low-rank residual variants to a fundamentally different gating family: `multi_branch_gated` at `K=24, EF=12` may outperform prior single-gate mid-K attempts by letting several gated branches specialize before the final top-k, improving the K=24 Pareto point without increasing K or EF.","summary":"Run one architecture-only experiment at the frontier-relevant mid-K band: `multi_branch_gated` with the settled low-EF recipe (`K=24`, `EF=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=3.2e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0`). This satisfies the severe-stagnation policy by trying a fundamentally different architecture rather than another minor scalar tweak, and targets a smaller-K non-dominated tradeoff instead of the K=128 anchor.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"multi_branch_gated","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"I avoided another LR/aux micro-sweep because the search has stalled for 7 rounds and policy requires an architecture jump. I also kept K fixed at 24 so this is a clean architecture comparison against the current frontier-relevant slot, with all recipe fields pinned to avoid launcher drift.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"multi_branch_gated"},{"key":"K","value":"24"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 42 should open a new architecture family because severe stagnation has reached 7 consecutive non-improving rounds.","Use a strict architecture-only comparison at K=24, EF=12 with all recipe fields pinned explicitly to avoid env drift.","`multi_branch_gated` is available in the current codebase and represents a materially different branch-mixing support-selection mechanism from the recent low-rank residual family sweep."],"next_hypotheses":["If `multi_branch_gated` is competitive but misses slightly at K=24, test the same family at K=16 to see whether branch specialization helps more at tighter budgets.","If it clearly loses at K=24, reject this family quickly and move to another fundamentally different non-lowrank architecture rather than returning to scalar sweeps.","If it wins at K=24, follow with K=16 or K=32 to map whether the gain is localized or broad across the mid-K band."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0160.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"After `lowrank_two_stage_residual` also failed at `K=24, EF=16`, the severe-stagnation policy still points to another fundamentally different existing architecture rather than more recipe tuning. `lowrank_residual` is the strongest remaining low-K candidate because it removes the second-stage composition entirely and previously showed the best ultra-low-K robustness, so its simpler trunk-plus-residual path may scale more gracefully to the current `K=24, EF=16` slot than the more structured two-stage variants.","summary":"Run an architecture-only comparison at `K=24, EF=16` by switching to `lowrank_residual` while keeping optimizer, LR, aux loss, and preprocessing fixed at the current signum baseline. This continues the severe-stagnation recovery with a materially different existing family, targets a valuable smaller-K slot where a non-dominated point still matters, and avoids returning to minor optimizer or preprocessing tweaks that have not worked.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"pareto_tradeoff","family_name":"lowrank_residual","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This is a clean one-variable architecture probe and fits the current policy better than more Adam retuning or another preprocessing pass. The risk is that `lowrank_residual` may need smaller K to shine, but it still offers a meaningfully different inductive bias from the recently failed two-stage, multi-branch, gating, VQ, and soft-codebook families.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"24"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 160 continues severe-stagnation architecture search after `lowrank_two_stage_residual` also failed to open a new `K=24, EF=16` frontier point.","Hypothesis: `lowrank_residual` is the next most informative fundamentally different low-K family because its simpler single-stage low-rank residual path may recover a better small-K tradeoff than the recently exhausted multi-stage and structured-selection variants under the fixed modern signum recipe."],"next_hypotheses":["If `lowrank_residual` is competitive at `K=24`, follow with `K=16` on the same family to test whether its simpler inductive bias helps further down the frontier.","If it is close but still behind the bucketed backbone, test another fundamentally different existing family at `K=24` rather than returning to scalar recipe tweaks.","If it clearly loses at `K=24`, deprioritize plain low-rank residual coding in the current EF=16 regime and continue severe-stagnation search with the next distinct architecture."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0071.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"`lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` has now beaten the `K=1` anchor, so the next question is whether the same hybrid can also improve `K=2` and begin subsuming the current `lowrank_soft_codebook_residual` low-K band.","summary":"Run one controlled architecture comparison at `K=2` with `lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual`, keeping `EF=12`, `signum`, `LR=3.2e-3`, and `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` fixed so the only changed dimension relative to the current `K=2` frontier point is architecture.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"pareto_fvu","family_name":"lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"incubating","self_review":"This is the cleanest follow-up after a new-family win at the endpoint. It tests whether the hybrid is just a `K=1` specialist or the start of a broader replacement for the existing low-K winner, without mixing in any recipe drift.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"2"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 71 tests whether `lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual`, newly on the frontier at `K=1`, can also improve the `K=2` slot under the same fixed recipe.","Keep architecture and recipe fixed (`EF=12`, `signum`, `LR=3.2e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0`) so this is a clean same-`K` architecture comparison against the current `K=2` frontier point.","Success criterion is beating the current `K=2` frontier anchor (`lowrank_soft_codebook_residual`, FVU `0.16154605150222778`) or at least establishing the hybrid as clearly competitive beyond the endpoint."],"next_hypotheses":["If `K=2` wins, test `K=4` to map whether the hybrid can replace `lowrank_soft_codebook_residual` across more of the low-K frontier.","If `K=2` is close but slightly behind, consider one confirmatory rerun before treating the hybrid as a `K=1` specialist.","If `K=2` clearly loses, retain the hybrid as the `K=1` endpoint winner and keep `lowrank_soft_codebook_residual` for `K>=2`."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0165.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"After plain residual, routed residual, bucketed residual, and single-stage soft-codebook variants all failed at `K=24, EF=16`, the next severe-stagnation move should still be a fundamentally different existing architecture rather than another recipe tweak. `lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` is the strongest remaining candidate because it changes the two-stage composition itself instead of only changing routing or support allocation, and its earlier `K=24` prototype result was closer to viability than most recent recovery probes, so a clean mainline comparison at the current slot is still justified.","summary":"Run an architecture-only comparison at `K=24, EF=16` by switching to `lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` while keeping optimizer, LR, aux loss, and preprocessing fixed at the current signum baseline. This continues severe-stagnation recovery with a materially different existing family, targets the valuable `K=24` frontier slot, and tests whether asymmetric two-stage composition can outperform the recently exhausted residual, routed, bucketed, and plain soft-codebook paths.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"pareto_tradeoff","family_name":"lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This is a clean single-variable architecture probe and remains more policy-consistent than returning to optimizer or preprocessing after repeated misses. The main risk is that the family already looked slightly weak in earlier prototype testing, but it still has one of the best unresolved `K=24` priors among the remaining distinct architectures and deserves one controlled modern comparison before being ruled out.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"24"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 165 continues severe-stagnation architecture search after plain single-stage soft-codebook residual also failed to improve the `K=24, EF=16` lane.","Hypothesis: `lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` is the next most informative remaining architecture because asymmetric stage allocation may scale better at `K=24` than the recently exhausted symmetric two-stage, routed, bucketed, residual-only, and single-stage codebook variants under the fixed signum recipe."],"next_hypotheses":["If `lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` is competitive at `K=24`, follow with `K=16` on the same family to test whether the asymmetric stage split helps further down the frontier.","If it is close but still behind the bucketed soft-codebook backbone, test another fundamentally different existing family at `K=24` rather than returning to scalar recipe tweaks.","If it clearly loses at `K=24`, deprioritize asymmetric two-stage soft-codebook composition in the current EF=16 regime and continue severe-stagnation search with the next distinct architecture."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/15_20260326_190606/logs/agent_action_0001.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"With an empty EF=12 frontier, the highest-value Round 1 move is to establish a clean `topk` anchor at the policy reference recipe before any LR or optimizer sweep. A full baseline run at `ARCHITECTURE=topk K=128 EXPANSION_FACTOR=12 OPTIMIZER=signum LR=8e-4` will give the first trustworthy curve shape for this regime and prevent later tuning rounds from being confounded by an unverified starting point.","summary":"Run the exact mainline `topk` clean baseline as the first EF=12 anchor: `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=8e-4`, with the standard topk defaults pinned in `env_overrides`. This keeps the family fixed, avoids premature search-space expansion, and creates the curve reference needed for the next step in the recommended order: LR tuning if the baseline is healthy.","change_type":"no_change","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This follows the round-1 policy exactly: stay on the current mainline family, start with a clean baseline, avoid coupling variables, and do not edit code without evidence of a blocker. The main downside is low novelty, but that is acceptable because the frontier is empty and the baseline curve is currently the missing decision anchor.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"8e-4"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.03125"},{"key":"DEAD_FEATURE_THRESHOLD","value":"10000000"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"0"},{"key":"HOOKPOINTS","value":"layers.[3].self_attn.o_proj"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 1 starts from an empty EF=12 frontier, so the first priority is a clean topk anchor rather than an exploratory family jump.","The active mainline reference recipe is `ARCHITECTURE=topk K=128 EXPANSION_FACTOR=12 OPTIMIZER=signum LR=8e-4`.","Use the resulting training curve shape, not just final FVU, to decide whether the next mainline move should be an LR increase, LR decrease, or optimizer change."],"next_hypotheses":["If the curve is smooth and still improving late, try a modest higher-LR topk follow-up while keeping family, K, optimizer, and EF fixed.","If the curve is noisy or unstable, try a modest lower-LR topk follow-up before changing optimizer.","If the baseline underperforms despite a healthy curve, keep topk fixed and test the next optimizer in the recommended order rather than changing K early."],"primary_variable":"other_param"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0154.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"After both plain and grouped soft-codebook variants failed at `K=24`, the next severe-stagnation step should be a fundamentally different existing architecture rather than more tuning on the same representation family. `lowrank_residual_vq` is the strongest remaining candidate for this slot because it replaces soft-codebook mixing with discrete residual quantization, which could yield a different small-K Pareto tradeoff under the fixed `EF=16` recipe even though its `K=32` result was not frontier-winning.","summary":"Run an architecture-only comparison at `K=24, EF=16` by switching to `lowrank_residual_vq` while keeping optimizer, LR, aux loss, and preprocessing fixed at the current stable signum recipe. This follows the severe-stagnation requirement to stop minor tweaks, targets a valuable smaller-K slot where a non-dominated result would still matter, and tests a materially different coding mechanism after repeated soft-codebook-family failures.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"pareto_tradeoff","family_name":"lowrank_residual_vq","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This is a clean single-variable architecture probe using an already registered family. The main risk is that residual-VQ remains weaker than the best soft-codebook backbone, but it is a more defensible next move than further optimizer or preprocessing sweeps after those already failed. Choosing `K=24` keeps pressure on the low-K frontier rather than revisiting already-covered `K=32` and higher slots.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_residual_vq"},{"key":"K","value":"24"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 154 continues severe-stagnation recovery by testing `lowrank_residual_vq` at `K=24, EF=16` after multiple soft-codebook-family architecture probes at the same slot failed.","This round isolates architecture only: discrete residual quantization versus soft-codebook composition under the same signum `LR=3.2e-3` recipe.","If `lowrank_residual_vq` also loses clearly at `K=24`, treat residual-VQ as noncompetitive in the current small-K EF=16 lane and continue to the next fundamentally different existing family rather than returning to minor tweaks."],"next_hypotheses":["If `lowrank_residual_vq` is competitive at `K=24`, follow with `K=16` on the same family to see whether discrete residual coding improves the low-K tradeoff curve further down the frontier.","If it is close but still behind the bucketed backbone, test `lowrank_jumprelu_residual` at `K=24` as another structurally different sparsity mechanism rather than returning to scalar tuning.","If it clearly loses at `K=24`, deprioritize residual-VQ in the current EF=16 regime and move to the next fundamentally different existing architecture."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0124.json:29:        "key": "ARCHITECTURE",
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0033.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"`lowrank_residual` has prior evidence as the strongest ultra-low-K family, so after the routed branch was blocked by a behavioral-diff policy rejection, the next substantial move is a clean architecture-only comparison against the current `K=4` lane. Testing `lowrank_residual` at `K=4, EF=12` under the established low-K optimization recipe may produce a better small-K Pareto point than `lowrank_two_stage_residual`.","summary":"Run a pure architecture comparison at `K=4, EF=12` by switching from `lowrank_two_stage_residual` to `lowrank_residual` while keeping optimizer, learning rate, expansion factor, and aux fixed to a controlled low-K recipe.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"smaller_k","family_name":"lowrank_residual","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This follows the severe-stagnation guidance to stop minor tweaks and try a fundamentally different architecture. `lowrank_residual` is the best-supported alternative family for the ultra-low-K regime, and `K=4` is the cleanest target because it is frontier-relevant and avoids the routed family's current integration blocker.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"4"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 33 abandons the blocked `routed_lowrank_two_stage_residual` branch after the behavioral-diff policy rejection and opens a new substantial architecture comparison: `lowrank_residual` at `K=4, EF=12` under the controlled low-K recipe."],"next_hypotheses":["If `lowrank_residual` wins at `K=4`, continue the same architecture-only comparison at `K=2`.","If it is close but slightly worse at `K=4`, keep the family active and test `K=2` before rejecting it.","If it clearly loses at `K=4`, return to `lowrank_two_stage_residual` and open a different substantial architecture branch rather than more scalar sweeps."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0147.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Six non-improving rounds mean the soft-codebook family is likely saturated under the current recipe, so the next probe should be a genuinely different representation mechanism rather than another scalar adjustment. `lowrank_residual_vq` is the strongest remaining fundamentally different existing family to test at `K=32, EF=16` because it replaces soft top-k composition with residual vector quantization structure, which could trade capacity more effectively in the low-K regime even though earlier lower-K probes were only moderately competitive.","summary":"Run an architecture-only comparison at `K=32, EF=16` by switching from the current bucketed soft-codebook backbone to `lowrank_residual_vq` while keeping optimizer, LR, aux loss, and preprocessing fixed.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"lowrank_residual_vq","family_stage":"incubating","self_review":"This follows the severe-stagnation instruction to stop minor tweaks and try a fundamentally different existing architecture. I kept `K=32` as the highest-value exposed EF=16 slot and pinned the rest of the recipe so the outcome isolates whether a discrete residual-VQ style code is a better low-K inductive bias than the exhausted soft-codebook variants.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_residual_vq"},{"key":"K","value":"32"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 147 continues severe-stagnation recovery by testing a fundamentally different existing family at the key `K=32, EF=16` slot instead of further tweaking the exhausted bucketed soft-codebook recipe.","`lowrank_residual_vq` is selected as a discrete residual-code alternative to soft-codebook architectures; even though prior lower-K results were not frontier-winning, `K=32` is a more forgiving slot and may reveal a different Pareto tradeoff under the fixed EF=16 regime."],"next_hypotheses":["If `lowrank_residual_vq` is competitive at `K=32`, follow with `K=24` or `K=16` to see whether its discrete structure creates a better small-K frontier than soft-codebook families.","If it is close but still worse than bucketed, shift the next round to a non-architecture axis such as preprocessing or optimizer on the best current bucketed anchor.","If it clearly loses at `K=32`, treat residual-VQ-style coding as noncompetitive in the current regime and move to the next underexplored training axis rather than more architecture churn."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0022.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The stronger `LR=3.2e-3` recipe that improved the `lowrank_two_stage_residual` `K=32, EF=12` anchor may transfer to a smaller-K frontier slot, so reducing only `K` from 32 to 24 should test whether the current `K=24` point (`FVU=0.09643366932868958`) is optimization-limited rather than architecture-limited.","summary":"Aux is now settled back to `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` on the active anchor, so the next clean move is a pure `K` reduction from the latest executed recipe. This directly targets the Pareto frontier objective by probing whether the improved anchor recipe can create a better non-dominated `K=24` point without changing architecture, width, optimizer, or aux settings.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_k","family_name":"lowrank_two_stage_residual","family_stage":"active","self_review":"This is policy-compliant because only `K` changes relative to round 21. The main risk is that `LR=3.2e-3` may be specific to `K=32`, but that is exactly the transfer question worth answering before spending another code round or broader sweep.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_two_stage_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"24"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 21 re-established `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` as the best-known setting on the `K=32, EF=12, LR=3.2e-3` anchor.","Round 22 should test pure `K` transfer from the improved anchor recipe to `K=24` instead of reopening aux sweeps or adding code changes."],"next_hypotheses":["If `K=24` with `LR=3.2e-3` beats the current `K=24` frontier point, continue the same single-variable transfer pattern to `K=16`.","If it underperforms clearly, conclude that the higher LR is `K`-dependent and keep `LR=1.6e-3` for smaller-K lanes.","If it is close but noisy, prioritize a confirming rerun before changing another variable."],"primary_variable":"k"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0006.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Keeping `lowrank_two_stage_residual` fixed and dropping only `K` from 4 to 2 will test whether this family remains Pareto-relevant in the extreme low-K regime, identifying where its low-support frontier breaks down.","summary":"Continue the controlled same-family sweep with a parameter-only run at `K=2`, while pinning the established recipe (`ARCHITECTURE=lowrank_two_stage_residual`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=1.6e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0`). The `K=4` result was still keep-worthy, so the next most informative move is to probe the next lower support level before changing architecture.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"smaller_k","family_name":"lowrank_two_stage_residual","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This keeps variable isolation intact, continues a productive low-K mapping run, and answers the most immediate frontier question before spending a round on a new family.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_two_stage_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"2"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 6 extends the controlled `lowrank_two_stage_residual` K sweep from 4 to 2 with all other recipe fields pinned.","The family has remained keep-worthy at every lower-K step so far, so testing `K=2` is the highest-information continuation before branching to routed variants or new families."],"next_hypotheses":["If `K=2` stays competitive, continue to `K=1` on the same family to locate the endpoint of this architecture's low-K tail.","If `K=2` degrades sharply, shift back to the 16-24 regime and test a routed variant for better support allocation.","If `K=2` is borderline but promising, keep the family fixed and tune stage allocation rather than changing the broader recipe."],"primary_variable":"k"}
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0071.json:29:        "key": "ARCHITECTURE",
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0115_repair_2.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"At K=24, the current two-stage soft-codebook backbone may be wasting scarce support by splitting K evenly across stages. A new `lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` family that allocates more of K to the first sparse pass and keeps a smaller refinement pass could beat the K=24 anchor by using the strongest existing backbone but changing the stage budget structurally for the small-K regime.","summary":"Repaired the original experiment again without redesigning it. The new blocker was an implementation error in the concrete class: `math.ceil` was used without importing `math` in `sparsify/sparse_coder.py`. That import is now added, and the exact instantiate/forward/backward smoke test passed again at `architecture=lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual, K=24, EF=12`, so this specific NameError is cleared and the original run contract remains unchanged.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This repair stayed within `sparsify/` and fixed the concrete runtime blocker rather than changing the experiment. Registration and smoke validation remain intact; the resolved issue was purely an implementation NameError during trainer construction.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"24"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":["sparsify/config.py","sparsify/sparse_coder.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Repair round 115 attempt 2 fixed a new implementation blocker for `lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual`: added the missing `math` import used by the asymmetric stage-budget logic in `sparsify/sparse_coder.py`.","The architecture registration chain remains complete, and the exact smoke test still passes for `architecture=lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual, K=24, EF=12` on CUDA after this fix.","The failure mode has changed from unknown-architecture to a repaired NameError; if the next full run fails, treat it as a new runtime/training blocker rather than reopening registration repair."],"next_hypotheses":["If `lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` trains cleanly and is competitive at K=24, follow with K=16 to test whether front-loaded sparse budgeting helps more under tighter sparsity.","If the full training run now fails with a different runtime or autograd issue, repair that architecture-specific blocker while keeping the same family and env overrides.","If it trains successfully but clearly loses at K=24, continue severe-stagnation search with another structurally different new family rather than returning to minor tweaks."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/round_summaries/round_0013.json:29:        "key": "ARCHITECTURE",
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0085.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The current evidence says the soft-codebook coarse residual is the right ingredient at `K=8`, while the fixed two-stage split becomes harmful once the sparse budget gets very small. The next single hypothesis is to add a new `lowrank_gated_soft_codebook_residual` family that keeps the winning soft-codebook coarse correction but replaces the rigid second sparse stage with gated support selection, aiming to beat the current `K=8` anchor under the same recipe.","summary":"Implement and run one new-family experiment at `K=8` with `lowrank_gated_soft_codebook_residual`, using the existing `lowrank_soft_codebook_residual` coarse codebook path plus the gated residual selector pattern from `lowrank_gated_residual`. Keep `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=3.2e-3`, and `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` fixed. Success criterion: beat the current `K=8` frontier anchor FVU (`0.12280897796154022`) and show that better low-K support allocation, not an extra refinement stage, is the missing ingredient.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"frontier_fvu","family_name":"lowrank_gated_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"incubating","self_review":"This is a cleaner next branch than retrying `K=4`: that question was already answered, and the new persistent K constraint forbids returning to `K=5/6/7/9/10/12`. The proposal changes exactly one main variable, architecture, while holding the successful low-K recipe fixed and targeting the most important allowed comparison point, `K=8`.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_gated_soft_codebook_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"8"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":["/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/config.py","/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/sparse_coder.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Round 85 should open a new low-K family at an allowed K value after `lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` lost the direct `K=4` comparison and the persistent K restriction now limits future runs to {4, 8, 16, 24, 32, 64, 96, 128}.","New hypothesis: at `K=8`, keep the soft-codebook coarse residual that already wins in this lane, but replace the rigid two-stage sparse split with gated support selection so the model can spend the full sparse budget on the most useful residual features.","The `K=4` miss suggests the two-stage soft-codebook family’s useful low-K regime does not extend to direct same-K wins at the floor; future low-K work should target allowed anchors such as `K=8` rather than continuing illegal intermediate-K interpolation."],"next_hypotheses":["If `lowrank_gated_soft_codebook_residual` wins at `K=8`, test the same family at `K=16` to see whether the gated variant improves the existing hybrid across the lower allowed-K lane.","If it is close but slightly behind at `K=8`, do one confirmatory rerun before deciding whether the idea is noise-sensitive or genuinely inferior.","If it clearly loses at `K=8`, conclude that soft-codebook plus gating is not the missing low-K ingredient and shift to a different mechanism rather than another small architectural variation."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0037.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"`lowrank_gated_residual` at `K=16` missed the current frontier by only a small margin, so the failure may be band-specific rather than a clean rejection of the family at `EF=12`. Increasing only `K` from `16` to `24` under the same settled recipe tests whether gating becomes beneficial in the adjacent mid-K regime and can beat the current `K=24` `lowrank_two_stage_residual` point.","summary":"Run a pure-`K` follow-up on `lowrank_gated_residual` by keeping architecture, expansion factor, optimizer, learning rate, and aux fixed to the round-36 recipe and changing only `K` from `16` to `24`. This checks whether the gated branch is competitive in the nearby transition band before abandoning the family.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"lowrank_gated_residual","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This follows the explicit guidance for a close-but-worse architecture result: test one adjacent `K` before rejecting the family. It changes exactly one primary variable relative to round 36, keeps the comparison controlled, and probes a frontier-relevant slot where slightly higher support may let the gate branch pay off.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_gated_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"24"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 37 treats the round-36 `lowrank_gated_residual` result at `K=16` as a close miss rather than an immediate rejection and tests one adjacent `K` under the same controlled recipe.","The goal is to determine whether gating helps specifically in the `K=24, EF=12` transition band before closing this family and moving on to another substantial architecture branch."],"next_hypotheses":["If `lowrank_gated_residual` wins at `K=24`, continue the same controlled family comparison at `K=32` or rerun once for confirmation before any scalar sweep.","If it is again close but slightly worse at `K=24`, reject the family at `EF=12` and open a different substantial architecture branch.","If it clearly loses at `K=24`, stop exploring this family in the low-EF lane and pivot to another materially different architecture rather than minor tweaks."],"primary_variable":"k"}
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0132.json:29:        "key": "ARCHITECTURE",
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0055.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"After routed, gated, discrete, and low-rank variants all failed badly at `K=24`, the next severe-stagnation move should test a fundamentally different structured sparsity family without trunks, gates, or codebooks. `bucketed_topk` at `K=24, EF=12` may improve the mid-K tradeoff by partitioning activations into simpler local competition pools before selection, potentially reducing redundant support allocation versus plain global top-k.","summary":"Run a pure architecture comparison at `K=24, EF=12` with `bucketed_topk` under the pinned recipe `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=3.2e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0`. This stays within severe-stagnation policy by making another architecture-only jump instead of any scalar tweak or repair round, while keeping evaluation anchored on the frontier-relevant mid-K slot.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"bucketed_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"I avoided further low-rank refinements because the recent low-rank-adjacent branch `bucketed_lowrank_residual` already came close but still lost, and policy says to stop minor tweaks. I also avoided code edits because recent repair attempts were policy-rejected; this keeps the round cleanly architecture-only with all recipe fields pinned.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"bucketed_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"24"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 55 continues severe-stagnation recovery with a pure `bucketed_topk` architecture test after `routed` also failed badly at K=24.","Keep the run pinned at `K=24, EF=12, signum, LR=3.2e-3, AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` so architecture is the only primary variable.","`bucketed_topk` tests whether structured local competition without low-rank trunks, gates, or discrete codebooks works better in the mid-K regime than the recent losing branches."],"next_hypotheses":["If `bucketed_topk` is competitive but slightly worse at K=24, test it at K=16 to see whether local competition helps more under tighter sparsity.","If `bucketed_topk` clearly loses at K=24, retire this structured-topk branch and move to another fundamentally different built-in family rather than any scalar sweep.","If `bucketed_topk` wins at K=24, follow with K=16 or K=32 to map whether the gain generalizes across the mid-K band."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0136.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The `K=32` bucketed backbone appears sensitive to LR, but the moderate reduction to `1.6e-3` was only a slight regression rather than a collapse. In exploitation mode, the next clean test is an aux-only sweep on the same strongest small-K recipe: adding a small `AUXK_ALPHA=0.01` may improve feature utilization enough to lower FVU without changing sparsity cost or reopening architecture search.","summary":"Run a pure auxiliary-loss sweep on `bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` at `K=32, EF=16`, keeping `signum` and `LR=3.2e-3` fixed while changing only `AUXK_ALPHA` from `0.0` to `0.01`. This follows the stagnation guidance to exploit the current best family and keeps focus on the most valuable exposed smaller-K frontier point.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This is the most disciplined next exploitation step after the mild LR regression at K32: change one parameter only, stay on the current best family, and target the smallest active frontier slot. I am pivoting from further aggressive LR reduction to aux because the latest result suggests the recipe is not badly unstable, so utilization shaping is a better next lever than pushing LR far below the known-good baseline.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"32"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.01"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 136 stays in exploitation mode on `bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` and shifts from LR to aux tuning after `LR=1.6e-3` produced only a slight K32 regression rather than a catastrophic failure.","Keep the target at `K=32` because improving the smallest exposed non-dominated point remains higher value than tuning the stronger K64/K96/K128 anchors.","This round isolates `AUXK_ALPHA=0.01` under the established `signum`, `LR=3.2e-3`, `EF=16` recipe to test whether a small utilization prior can tighten the K32 tradeoff."],"next_hypotheses":["If `AUXK_ALPHA=0.01` improves the K32 bucketed point, follow with `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0625` on the same recipe to map whether the gain continues with stronger aux pressure.","If `AUXK_ALPHA=0.01` is neutral or worse, revert to `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` as the preferred K32 recipe and then test one of the remaining much-lower LRs only if exploitation still requires more scalar sweeps.","If aux materially worsens convergence at K32, treat the current bucketed frontier as preferring no auxiliary pressure and refocus remaining exploitation on LR only."],"primary_variable":"other_param"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/round_summaries/round_0167.json:29:        "key": "ARCHITECTURE",
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0153.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"After the plain non-bucketed two-stage soft-codebook family also lost at `K=24`, the next severe-stagnation move should be another fundamentally different existing architecture rather than more recipe tuning. `lowrank_grouped_soft_codebook_residual` is the strongest remaining structurally distinct soft-codebook variant for this slot because grouped competition changes capacity allocation more materially than scalar hyperparameters and may produce a better small-K Pareto tradeoff under the fixed EF=16 recipe.","summary":"Run an architecture-only comparison at `K=24, EF=16` by switching to `lowrank_grouped_soft_codebook_residual` while keeping optimizer, LR, aux loss, and preprocessing fixed at the current stable recipe. This follows policy guidance to stop minor tweaks after prolonged stagnation, keeps the probe on a valuable smaller-K slot, and tests whether grouped selection can outperform both the exhausted bucketed backbone and the weaker plain two-stage variant in the current EF=16 lane.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"pareto_tradeoff","family_name":"lowrank_grouped_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This is a clean single-variable architecture test using an already registered family. The main risk is that grouped competition may again be too restrictive, but that is still a more policy-consistent next action than continuing optimizer or preprocessing tweaks after they both failed. `K=24` remains the highest-value unclaimed smaller-K slot where a non-dominated tradeoff would still matter even without beating the `K=32` anchor on absolute FVU.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_grouped_soft_codebook_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"24"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 153 continues severe-stagnation recovery by trying another fundamentally different existing architecture at `K=24, EF=16` after plain `lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` also failed to open a new frontier point.","`lowrank_grouped_soft_codebook_residual` is selected because grouping changes support allocation more materially than recent scalar recipe tweaks while staying within the existing registered family set.","Keep the recipe pinned to signum + `LR=3.2e-3` + no Hadamard so attribution stays on the grouped architecture rather than optimizer or preprocessing drift."],"next_hypotheses":["If `lowrank_grouped_soft_codebook_residual` is competitive at `K=24`, follow with `K=16` on the same family to map whether grouping improves the low-K tradeoff curve further down the frontier.","If it is close but still behind the bucketed backbone, test another structurally distinct existing family such as `lowrank_residual_vq` or `lowrank_jumprelu_residual` at `K=24` rather than returning to scalar tuning.","If it clearly loses at `K=24`, treat grouped soft-codebook routing as noncompetitive in the current EF=16 small-K lane and move to the next fundamentally different existing architecture."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0155.json:29:        "key": "ARCHITECTURE",
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0106.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The round-105 crash was a registration/integration bug rather than a scientific negative; after wiring `lowrank_gated_soft_codebook_residual` into config and factory dispatch and implementing the concrete sparse coder, rerunning the same K=24, EF=12 recipe will cleanly test whether gated support selection improves the mid-K soft-codebook Pareto lane.","summary":"Repaired the unknown-architecture blocker for `lowrank_gated_soft_codebook_residual` under `sparsify/` only. Added the architecture to `sparsify/config.py`, added `_get_sae_class()` dispatch in `sparsify/sparse_coder.py`, and implemented `LowRankGatedSoftCodebookResidualSparseCoder` by combining the existing soft-codebook residual trunk with the existing gated sparse selector. Verified with the exact integration smoke target `(architecture=lowrank_gated_soft_codebook_residual, K=24, EF=12)`: instantiate, forward, and backward all succeeded on CUDA. Next action is a full rerun of the original architecture-comparison experiment with minimal overrides to measure the family rather than the previous registration bug.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"lowrank_gated_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This stays within one hypothesis: repair the crashed family and rerun the exact intended comparison. I did not change launcher semantics or unrelated recipes. The exact smoke test passed, so the parse/dispatch chain is now closed; the remaining uncertainty is scientific performance under training, not integration.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_gated_soft_codebook_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"24"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":["sparsify/config.py","sparsify/sparse_coder.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Repaired `lowrank_gated_soft_codebook_residual` registration chain: whitelist, factory dispatch, and concrete class now exist under `sparsify/`.","Exact smoke test passed for `lowrank_gated_soft_codebook_residual` at `(K=24, EF=12)` with forward/backward on CUDA, so round-105's `Unknown architecture` crash should no longer recur.","Round 106 should rerun the original `lowrank_gated_soft_codebook_residual` architecture comparison at `K=24` with the minimal fixed recipe to evaluate the family rather than the prior integration bug."],"next_hypotheses":["If `lowrank_gated_soft_codebook_residual` is competitive at `K=24`, run the same fixed recipe at `K=32` to see whether gating helps across the mid-K band.","If it runs cleanly but clearly loses at `K=24`, continue severe-stagnation search with another fundamentally different existing family rather than more scalar tuning.","If the full run fails with a new runtime/autograd issue, treat that as the next blocker and repair it before drawing any conclusion about the family."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0011.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"At ultra-low sparsity, switching only the architecture from `lowrank_two_stage_residual` to `lowrank_residual` at the same `K=1, EF=12` will lower FVU and may reclaim a non-dominated frontier point, since prior history suggests `lowrank_residual` is stronger in the K<=4 regime.","summary":"Run a parameter-only architecture swap at the current ultra-low-K anchor, with every other recipe field explicitly pinned to avoid controller drift.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"lowrank_residual","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This isolates a single primary variable: architecture. I pinned `K`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR`, `OPTIMIZER`, `LR`, and `AUXK_ALPHA` explicitly so the controller should not infer a mixed K/EF change again.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"1"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 11 should test whether `lowrank_residual` beats `lowrank_two_stage_residual` at the already-mapped ultra-low-K anchor `K=1, EF=12` under a fully pinned recipe.","Recent policy rejections came from variable-isolation drift, so all recipe fields that matter for comparability are explicitly pinned in env overrides."],"next_hypotheses":["If `lowrank_residual` wins at `K=1`, continue with the same architecture at `K=2` only if needed to verify the ultra-low-K ordering under the current token budget.","If `lowrank_residual` ties or loses at `K=1`, keep `lowrank_two_stage_residual` as the current ultra-low-K family and shift the next isolated test to a different single variable such as architecture at `K=2` or `AUXK_ALPHA` cleanup within one fixed family.","If `lowrank_residual` is clearly better, treat it as the ultra-low-K mainline family and only then consider a controlled EF sweep from that family."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0012.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"At the ultra-low-K anchor, increasing only `AUXK_ALPHA` from the baseline to `0.03125` for `lowrank_two_stage_residual` at `K=1, EF=12` may improve feature usage enough to reduce FVU without changing sparsity cost, potentially strengthening the frontier endpoint.","summary":"Run a strictly single-variable follow-up from the latest successful ultra-low-K recipe by keeping architecture, K, EF, optimizer, and LR fixed and changing only `AUXK_ALPHA`.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"lowrank_two_stage_residual","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This avoids the recent isolation failures by staying on the current family and current K/EF anchor and changing only one scalar hyperparameter. It does not introduce code edits, architecture changes, or coupled K/EF moves.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_two_stage_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"1"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.03125"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 12 should recover from repeated isolation rejects by holding the latest successful `lowrank_two_stage_residual` ultra-low-K recipe fixed at `K=1, EF=12` and varying only `AUXK_ALPHA`.","This tests whether auxiliary feature encouragement can improve the `K=1` endpoint without altering sparsity cost or architecture, which is directly relevant to strengthening the Pareto frontier tail."],"next_hypotheses":["If `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125` improves `K=1`, test the same single-variable change at `K=2` to check whether the ultra-low-K tail consistently benefits.","If it hurts or is neutral at `K=1`, keep `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` as the ultra-low-K default and shift the next round to another isolated scalar on the same anchor.","If the gain is meaningful, consider a small `AUXK_ALPHA` refinement at the same anchor before changing family or EF."],"primary_variable":"auxk_alpha"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/round_summaries/round_0053.json:29:        "key": "ARCHITECTURE",
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0131.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Now that bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual has replaced the old high-K anchor at EF=16, the highest-value next test is whether an optimizer change can further improve a smaller-K frontier point without changing architecture or capacity; specifically, Adam on the strong K=32 bucketed backbone may reduce FVU enough to tighten the low-cost Pareto region.","summary":"Run a parameter-only optimizer ablation on the current K=32 bucketed backbone: keep architecture, K, EF, and LR fixed, and swap `signum` for `adam` to test whether optimizer choice improves the low-K frontier under the new EF=16 regime.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"mainline_optimizer_probe","self_review":"This follows the operator priority shift by probing optimizer rather than inventing a new architecture, and it keeps attribution clean by changing only the optimizer on an existing frontier model. Keeping LR fixed at 3.2e-3 makes the result easier to interpret, though it may understate Adam's ceiling if it needs a different tuned LR.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"32"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 131 should pivot from K-axis mapping to the operator-requested optimizer dimension now that bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual owns the EF=16 anchor and mid-K lane.","Probe optimizer on K=32 first because improving a smaller-K frontier point is more valuable than chasing an already-strong K=128 anchor, and K=32 is the cheapest currently exposed bucketed frontier slot."],"next_hypotheses":["If Adam improves K=32 materially, propagate the same optimizer test to K=64 on the bucketed family to see whether the gain generalizes across the mid-K frontier.","If Adam is neutral or worse at K=32 with fixed LR, keep signum as the bucketed default and pivot next to a preprocessing or loss-function ablation on the same K=32 backbone.","If Adam destabilizes training, avoid coupled LR retuning immediately and instead test a different optimizer that is more likely to behave well under the existing 3.2e-3 recipe."],"primary_variable":"optimizer"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0024.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"At `K=16, EF=12`, the apparent regression from `LR=1.6e-3` to `LR=3.2e-3` is small enough that the low-K lane may be noise-sensitive, so reverting only `LR` back to `1.6e-3` should confirm whether the better `K=16` recipe is the lower-LR setting before extending further down the frontier.","summary":"Round 23 did not show a clean transfer win at `K=16`; it landed slightly worse than the earlier `K=16` result despite matching the improved high-K recipe. The next disciplined step is a single-variable LR rollback at the same `K=16, EF=12` slot to confirm the better local optimizer setting before attempting `K=8`.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"lowrank_two_stage_residual","family_stage":"active","self_review":"This is a strict one-variable causal cleanup from the latest executed recipe, changing only `LR`. The main downside is that it is partly confirmatory rather than exploratory, but the `K=16` result is close enough that resolving optimizer sensitivity is higher value than blindly pushing the higher-LR recipe deeper into the low-K regime.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_two_stage_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"16"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 23 suggests the `LR=3.2e-3` transfer may stall by `K=16`; treat the difference versus the earlier `K=16` point as small enough to require a controlled rollback rather than a hard conclusion.","Round 24 should revert only `LR` from `3.2e-3` to `1.6e-3` at `lowrank_two_stage_residual, K=16, EF=12, AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` to settle the local optimizer choice cleanly."],"next_hypotheses":["If the `K=16` rollback to `LR=1.6e-3` recovers the better result, keep `LR=1.6e-3` for the low-K tail and then test a pure `K` reduction to `K=8`.","If `LR=1.6e-3` does not improve over round 23, conclude the `K=16` difference was mostly noise and consider a confirming rerun of the better of the two settings before moving on.","Once the `K=16` optimizer choice is settled, continue searching for a new non-dominated smaller-K point rather than reopening aux sweeps."],"primary_variable":"lr"}
research/history_archive/15_20260326_190606/logs/agent_action_0006.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"`adam` at the signum-tuned LR regressed enough that the current `topk` mainline should revert to the stronger `signum` anchor and advance to the next stage in the recommended order: loss shaping. Under the now-tuned `signum` regime, the inherited `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125` auxiliary pressure may be over-regularizing support usage, so removing it could improve reconstruction curve shape and final FVU at `K=128` without changing LUTurbo compatibility.","summary":"Keep the `topk` mainline anchor fixed at `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, and `LR=2.0e-3`, and change only the auxiliary-loss setting by setting `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0`. This asks one clean question after the optimizer check failed: whether the tuned signum topk recipe now works better without auxiliary sparsity shaping.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This keeps the family fixed, respects the single-variable rule, and moves to the next recommended stage after `adam` failed to beat the signum anchor. The main risk is that aux removal can improve early FVU while harming late utilization, so this run should be judged by the whole curve and support behavior rather than the final scalar alone.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"2.0e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"},{"key":"DEAD_FEATURE_THRESHOLD","value":"10000000"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"0"},{"key":"HOOKPOINTS","value":"layers.[3].self_attn.o_proj"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["`adam` at `K=128`, `EF=12`, `LR=2.0e-3` underperformed the signum anchor (`0.46458443999290466` vs `0.4522051215171814`), so `signum` remains the current optimizer winner for topk mainline.","Round 6 returns to the best signum anchor and starts the loss/preprocess stage with a single-variable probe on `AUXK_ALPHA`.","Evaluate this run by curve shape and late behavior as well as final FVU: if aux-free training descends faster early but stalls or destabilizes late, keep the original aux loss."],"next_hypotheses":["If `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` improves the curve and final FVU, keep the aux-free signum recipe as the new topk anchor before considering preprocessing.","If aux removal hurts late behavior or final FVU, restore `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125` and test a preprocessing change such as Hadamard only if the curve suggests representation conditioning is the next bottleneck.","If the loss/preprocess stage yields no gain, move to the K stage next and test whether a smaller `K` can offer a better LUTurbo tradeoff under the strongest confirmed topk recipe."],"primary_variable":"other_param"}
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0248.json:19:    "hypothesis": "\u5019\u9009 family: factorized_topk\u3002\u6700\u7ec8\u91cd\u6784\u516c\u5f0f\u4e3a x_hat = \u03a3_i \u03b1_i b_i\uff0c\u5176\u4e2d {b_i} \u6765\u81ea\u5355\u4e2a\u9759\u6001\u5411\u91cf\u5e93\uff1b\u4f4e\u79e9 factorized scorer \u53ea\u6539\u53d8\u5355\u6837\u672c\u5728\u7ebf\u4fa7\u7684\u6253\u5206\u4e0e\u9009\u62e9\u94fe\u8def\uff0c\u4e0d\u6539\u53d8 decoder \u7aef\u7684\u5355\u5e93\u67e5\u8868 + \u52a0\u6743\u6c42\u548c + \u9009\u62e9\u6027\u8865\u507f\u5bfc\u51fa\u5f62\u5f0f\uff0c\u56e0\u6b64\u53ef\u76f4\u63a5\u5bfc\u51fa\u5230 LUTurbo/Lottable \u63a8\u7406\u94fe\u8def\uff0c\u517c\u5bb9\u6027\u5224\u65ad\u4e3a\u76f4\u63a5\u517c\u5bb9\u3002\u76f8\u5bf9 reference_round=r247 \u53ea\u6539\u4e00\u4e2a env \u53c2\u6570 `K=32`\uff0c\u4fdd\u6301 `ARCHITECTURE=factorized_topk`\u3001`EXPANSION_FACTOR=1`\u3001`FACTORIZED_HIDDEN_DIM=96`\u3001`OPTIMIZER=signum`\u3001`LR=0.003` \u53ca\u5176\u4f59\u914d\u7f6e\u4e0d\u53d8\uff0c\u6d4b\u8bd5\u5728\u5df2\u786e\u8ba4 `K=96 -> 64` \u4ec5\u5e26\u6765\u6709\u9650 FVU \u9000\u5316\u540e\uff0c\u8fdb\u4e00\u6b65\u628a\u90e8\u7f72\u67e5\u8868\u6210\u672c\u538b\u5230\u7ea6 0.08x \u603b\u6210\u672c\u65f6\uff0cFVU \u662f\u5426\u4ecd\u7ef4\u6301\u5728\u540c\u4e00\u91cf\u7ea7\uff0c\u4ece\u800c\u786e\u5b9a\u8fd9\u6761\u8d85\u4f4e\u6210\u672c factorized scorer \u652f\u7ebf\u7684\u6700\u5de6\u53ef\u7528\u8fb9\u754c\u3002",
