research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0060_repair_1.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"A conditional mixture of residual dictionaries may recover the mid-K lane where fixed residual mechanisms have stalled: `lowrank_multi_branch_residual` keeps the strong low-rank trunk, then lets a learned sample-level router mix several residual scoring branches before final top-k selection, potentially matching heterogeneous residual regimes better than a single encoder.","summary":"Repaired `lowrank_multi_branch_residual` so the original round-60 experiment can run under DDP. The crash was caused by inherited `encoder.weight` and `encoder.bias` from `LowRankResidualSparseCoder` being unused in the new family, which triggered the prior-iteration reduction error. Patched `_mixed_acts()` so the inherited residual encoder is an always-on anchor branch alongside the routed branches, then re-ran the concrete factory-dispatch checks. Validation passed: all parameters now receive gradients, and the exact smoke target `architecture=lowrank_multi_branch_residual, K=24, EF=12` instantiates, runs forward, and backward successfully.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"lowrank_multi_branch_residual","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This is a repair only; the architecture name, hypothesis, and env overrides are unchanged. The fix addresses the precise DDP-unused-parameter blocker without redesigning the experiment. I also corrected the validation path by smoke-testing the actual architecture class through `_get_sae_class()` at the exact failing `(architecture, K, EF)` instead of relying on the base `SparseCoder` constructor.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_multi_branch_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"24"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":["sparsify/sparse_coder.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Repair round 60 attempt 1: `lowrank_multi_branch_residual` crashed under DDP because inherited `encoder.weight` and `encoder.bias` were unused in the forward pass.","Patched `lowrank_multi_branch_residual` so the inherited residual encoder participates as an always-on anchor branch in `_mixed_acts()`, eliminating the unused-parameter reduction bug.","Verified on the concrete architecture class via `_get_sae_class('lowrank_multi_branch_residual')` that all parameters now receive gradients.","Exact integration smoke passed for `lowrank_multi_branch_residual` at `K=24, EF=12` with forward/backward on the real architecture class."],"next_hypotheses":["Run the original `lowrank_multi_branch_residual` experiment again at the same pinned `K=24, EF=12, signum, LR=3.2e-3, AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` recipe now that the DDP blocker is fixed.","If the repaired run is competitive but slightly worse at `K=24`, test `K=16` to see whether conditional branch specialization helps more under tighter sparsity.","If the repaired run still fails, inspect the new failure mode directly rather than changing architecture or hyperparameters."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0140.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"After bucketed, plain two-stage, routed, and gated soft-codebook backbones all failed to beat the current `K=32, EF=16` bucketed point, the next severe-stagnation move should test a genuinely different existing architecture rather than return to scalar tweaks. `lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` is the strongest remaining soft-codebook-adjacent candidate by prior quality and may transfer better to `EF=16` at `K=32` by allocating capacity asymmetrically across stages instead of via buckets, routing, or gating.","summary":"Run an architecture-only comparison at `K=32, EF=16` with `lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual`, keeping `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=3.2e-3`, and `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` fixed. This follows the severe-stagnation guidance to stop minor tweaks and test a fundamentally different existing architecture on the most valuable exposed small-K frontier slot.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This is a policy-clean architecture-only move on the same high-value `K=32` target under fixed `EF=16`. I chose the asymmetric two-stage variant because it offers a real structural departure from the already-failed bucketed, routed, plain, and gated branches while still having a stronger prior than older discarded non-soft-codebook families.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"32"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 140 continues severe-stagnation recovery by testing `lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` at `K=32, EF=16` after the bucketed, plain two-stage, routed, and gated soft-codebook variants all failed to improve the current frontier point.","Keep optimizer, LR, and aux fixed so the result isolates architecture alone on the highest-value exposed small-K slot.","This run asks whether asymmetric stage allocation is a better inductive bias than bucketing, routing, or gating under the current EF=16 regime."],"next_hypotheses":["If `lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` improves the `K=32, EF=16` point, propagate it to `K=64` before returning to any recipe tuning.","If it is close but slightly worse at `K=32`, consider one preprocessing or optimizer probe on this asymmetric backbone rather than discarding it immediately.","If it clearly loses at `K=32`, treat the remaining soft-codebook architecture space as close to exhausted under the current recipe and pivot to under-explored runtime axes on the existing bucketed backbone."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/round_summaries/round_0136.json:29:        "key": "ARCHITECTURE",
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0133.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The runtime currently cannot test the operator-requested loss axis because `sparsify/trainer.py` hardcodes `loss = out.fvu + aux`. Add a minimal configurable `loss_fn` to `sparsify/` and test a robust reconstruction objective on the strongest low-K EF=16 backbone: `bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` at K=32. A Huber-style loss may reduce sensitivity to a small set of hard residual outliers and improve evaluated FVU at the smallest exposed frontier point without changing architecture or capacity.","summary":"Make a scoped code change under `sparsify/` to add a configurable training loss, then run the current K=32 bucketed backbone with `LOSS_FN=huber` as the only scientific variable change.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"mainline_loss_probe","self_review":"This is the cleanest way to satisfy the operator priority shift after Adam and Hadamard both regressed: loss-function exploration is currently impossible without a small runtime edit. The proposed edit is tightly scoped to `sparsify/`, preserves default behavior with `loss_fn=fvu`, and keeps the experiment scientifically single-variable once the knob exists.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"32"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"},{"key":"LOSS_FN","value":"huber"},{"key":"HUBER_DELTA","value":"1.0"}],"touched_files":["sparsify/config.py","sparsify/trainer.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Round 133 should unlock the operator-requested loss-function axis by adding a minimal configurable `loss_fn` in `sparsify/` while preserving the current default `fvu` path.","Use the K=32 bucketed EF=16 signum backbone as the first loss probe because smaller-K Pareto improvements are more valuable than further perturbing the already-strong K=96/K=128 anchor points.","Keep the implementation minimal: validate `loss_fn` in config, preserve existing behavior for `fvu`, and add a robust `huber` alternative computed in the trainer so the architecture code stays unchanged."],"next_hypotheses":["If Huber training improves K=32 materially, propagate the same loss function to K=64 on the bucketed family to see whether the gain extends across the mid-K frontier.","If Huber is neutral or worse, keep `fvu` as the default and consider a second loss probe such as normalized L1 on the same K=32 bucketed recipe.","If the loss-function code path is unstable or creates invalid comparisons, revert to the default `fvu` path and resume exploration on the remaining supported runtime axes."],"primary_variable":"loss_function"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0152.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"After eleven non-improving rounds, policy now favors a fundamentally different architecture rather than more recipe tweaking. `lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` is the strongest existing non-bucketed contender in the current EF=16 lane, and testing it at `K=24` may reveal a non-dominated lower-K tradeoff if the simpler global two-stage composition scales down more gracefully than the bucketed backbone.","summary":"Run an architecture-only comparison at `K=24, EF=16` by switching from the exhausted bucketed backbone to `lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` while keeping optimizer, LR, aux loss, and preprocessing fixed at the strongest known recipe. This satisfies the severe-stagnation directive to stop minor tweaks, targets a smaller-K slot that would be valuable if competitive, and uses an existing family that has shown the closest credible EF=16 behavior without introducing new code.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"pareto_tradeoff","family_name":"lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This is a clean one-variable architecture probe under the fixed launcher. The main risk is that the simpler non-bucketed family still trails the bucketed backbone at low K, but it is a more policy-consistent next step than another optimizer or preprocessing tweak after both just failed. Choosing `K=24` instead of repeating `K=32` increases the chance of discovering a genuinely useful new Pareto point rather than merely chasing a marginal quality gap at an already-covered slot.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"24"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 152 follows severe-stagnation policy by returning to a fundamentally different existing architecture after preprocessing and optimizer retune both failed on the bucketed backbone.","`lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` remains the most credible non-bucketed EF=16 family to probe, and `K=24` is a high-value smaller-K slot where a modest FVU increase could still produce a non-dominated tradeoff.","Keep the recipe pinned to signum + `LR=3.2e-3` + no Hadamard so attribution stays on architecture rather than another coupled training change."],"next_hypotheses":["If `lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` is competitive at `K=24`, follow with `K=16` on the same family to map whether the simpler two-stage backbone can extend the low-K frontier further than bucketed.","If it is close but still behind the bucketed family, test `lowrank_grouped_soft_codebook_residual` or another structurally distinct existing family at `K=24` rather than returning to scalar tuning.","If it clearly loses at `K=24`, treat plain two-stage soft-codebook as noncompetitive in the current EF=16 small-K lane and move to the next fundamentally different existing architecture."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/round_summaries/round_0083.json:29:        "key": "ARCHITECTURE",
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0040.json:20:    "summary": "Stay on the same `gated` mainline and continue the learning-rate sweep with one adjacent confirmation step. Keep `ARCHITECTURE=gated`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, and `OPTIMIZER=signum` fixed, explicitly pin the reference aux/runtime knobs, and raise only `LR` from `2.0e-3` to `2.4e-3`. Judge this round by full trajectory shape, not just terminal FVU: if early and mid training remain as smooth as Round 39 and the late descent goes lower than `0.148156`, then the LR optimum is still above the current anchor; if the curve gets noisier, flatter, or regresses, stop the LR branch and lock `2.0e-3` as the mainline setting.",
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0040.json:29:        "key": "ARCHITECTURE",
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0040.json:104:    "description": "Stay on the same `gated` mainline and continue the learning-rate sweep with one adjacent confirmation step. Keep `ARCHITECTURE=gated`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, and `OPTIMIZER=signum` fixed, explicitly pin the reference aux/runtime knobs, and raise only `LR` from `2.0e-3` to `2.4e-3`. Judge this round by full trajectory shape, not just terminal FVU: if early and mid training remain as smooth as Round 39 and the late descent goes lower than `0.148156`, then the LR optimum is still above the current anchor; if the curve gets noisier, flatter, or regresses, stop the LR branch and lock `2.0e-3` as the mainline setting.",
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0069.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"`lowrank_soft_codebook_residual` has now taken the frontier at `K=16`, `K=8`, `K=4`, and `K=2`; testing the same fixed recipe at `K=1` determines whether this family can cover the full low-K Pareto frontier and potentially beat the current `K=1` anchor from `lowrank_two_stage_residual`.","summary":"Run one controlled parameter-only experiment at `K=1` with `lowrank_soft_codebook_residual`, keeping `EF=12`, `signum`, `LR=3.2e-3`, and `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` fixed so `K` is the only changed variable.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"smaller_k","family_name":"lowrank_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This remains the strongest single-variable continuation. The family has produced four consecutive frontier wins as K decreased, so the highest-value next question is whether that dominance extends all the way to `K=1` before returning to broader architecture exploration.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_soft_codebook_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"1"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 69 tests whether `lowrank_soft_codebook_residual`, now on the frontier at `K=16`, `K=8`, `K=4`, and `K=2`, can extend to the extreme endpoint at `K=1` under the same fixed recipe.","Keep architecture and recipe fixed (`EF=12`, `signum`, `LR=3.2e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0`) so `K` is the only changing dimension.","Success criterion is beating the current `K=1` frontier anchor (`lowrank_two_stage_residual`, FVU `0.17282412946224213`) and confirming whether this family spans the full low-K frontier."],"next_hypotheses":["If `K=1` wins, treat `lowrank_soft_codebook_residual` as the dominant low-K family and shift focus back to mid-K/new-family search.","If `K=1` is close but slightly behind, consider one confirmatory rerun before concluding the family bottoms out at `K=2`.","If `K=1` clearly loses, keep `lowrank_soft_codebook_residual` as strongest in the `K=2-16` band and resume new-family search for the `K=1` slot."],"primary_variable":"k"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0169.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Under severe stagnation and the explicit operator shift away from architecture churn, the highest-information single-variable probe is preprocessing on the strongest small-K backbone: enabling Hadamard rotation on `bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` at `K=32, EF=16` may improve conditioning enough to lower FVU without giving up the strategically valuable small-K point.","summary":"Run a parameter-only preprocessing probe on the current best `K=32, EF=16` family by enabling `USE_HADAMARD=1` while pinning architecture, K, EF, optimizer, LR, and aux loss. This tests a materially under-explored dimension requested by the operator hints, keeps the experiment attributable to one change, and targets the more valuable small-K frontier slot rather than spending another round on high-K refinement or another weak architecture family.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This respects the current constraints: one hypothesis, no architecture invention, K chosen from the allowed set, EF pinned to 16, and all core recipe fields explicitly set in env overrides. Main risk: earlier whitening-style variants were unstable, so a pure rotation may still be neutral or harmful, but it is a much cleaner preprocessing probe than reviving another discarded family.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"32"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"1"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 169 should stop architecture churn and probe preprocessing instead, per operator guidance.","Use the strongest existing small-K backbone (`bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` at `K=32, EF=16`) so the Hadamard result is informative for frontier improvement rather than confounded by a weak family."],"next_hypotheses":["If Hadamard improves the `K=32` point, transfer the same preprocessing change to `K=64` on the same family to test whether the gain persists across the low/mid-K frontier.","If Hadamard is neutral or worse, keep preprocessing off for this backbone and shift the next round to a loss-shaping probe such as Matryoshka training on the same fixed `K=32, EF=16` recipe.","If Hadamard destabilizes training, deprioritize activation rotation in this regime and move to an optimizer-focused probe with an explicitly retuned LR rather than another architecture swap."],"primary_variable":"other_param"}
research/history_archive/15_20260326_190606/logs/agent_action_0005.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"After three consecutive FVU improvements from raising signum LR up to `2.0e-3`, the clean next mainline question is whether optimizer choice, not just step size, is now the limiting factor for `topk` at `K=128`. Switching from `signum` to `adam` while holding the tuned recipe fixed will reveal whether a different update rule can improve reconstruction further or whether signum remains the stronger backbone optimizer in this EF=12 regime.","summary":"Keep the `topk` mainline recipe fixed at `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, and `LR=2.0e-3`, and change only `OPTIMIZER` from `signum` to `adam`. This follows the recommended order by ending the current LR sweep and starting the optimizer-comparison stage with a single clean variable change.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This is the right point to test optimizer because the signum LR branch has improved repeatedly and the policy says optimizer comes next before loss or K. The main risk is that `adam` may need a different LR region, but that is acceptable for this round because the goal is to answer one question first: whether optimizer change is promising enough to justify a dedicated LR retune.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"},{"key":"LR","value":"2.0e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.03125"},{"key":"DEAD_FEATURE_THRESHOLD","value":"10000000"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"0"},{"key":"HOOKPOINTS","value":"layers.[3].self_attn.o_proj"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["The signum topk mainline improved monotonically across the LR sweep up to `LR=2.0e-3`, reaching `FVU=0.4522051215171814` at `K=128`, `EF=12`.","Round 5 starts the optimizer stage by switching only `OPTIMIZER` from `signum` to `adam` while keeping the tuned topk anchor otherwise fixed.","Interpret this run primarily by curve shape and stability versus the signum anchor: if `adam` is promising but mis-scaled, it should still show a plausible optimization trajectory worth one LR callback round."],"next_hypotheses":["If `adam` matches or beats the signum anchor with a healthy curve, keep `topk` fixed and run one LR retune round for `adam`.","If `adam` is worse but the curve looks smooth and undertrained, keep `topk` fixed and test a lower `adam` LR as the required optimizer-specific callback.","If `adam` is clearly unstable or uniformly worse throughout the curve, treat signum as the current optimizer winner and move to loss or preprocess only after the optimizer stage is exhausted."],"primary_variable":"optimizer"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/round_summaries/round_0170.json:29:        "key": "ARCHITECTURE",
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/logs/agent_action_0045.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"After repeated failures from residual/gating variants, relaxing the per-sample hard support constraint may recover a better mid-K tradeoff: `batch_topk` at `K=24, EF=12` could improve reconstruction efficiency over fixed-sample top-k and challenge the current `K=24` frontier point without increasing K or EF.","summary":"Run a pure architecture comparison at `K=24, EF=12` with `batch_topk` under the pinned recipe `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=3.2e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0`. This follows the severe-stagnation policy by trying a fundamentally different sparsity mechanism instead of any further scalar sweep.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"batch_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"I avoided LR, aux, K, and EF tweaks because ten no-improve rounds means minor tuning is exhausted. I also kept the comparison at K=24 so the readout stays directly comparable to the current frontier slot while testing a genuinely different support-allocation mechanism.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"batch_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"24"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.2e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 45 continues severe-stagnation recovery with another fundamentally different built-in family after `multi_branch_gated`, `jumprelu`, and `two_stage_residual` all failed badly at K=24.","Keep the run architecture-only at K=24, EF=12 with all recipe fields explicitly pinned.","`batch_topk` tests whether a looser support-budget allocation works better than strict per-sample top-k in the frontier-relevant mid-K regime."],"next_hypotheses":["If `batch_topk` is competitive but slightly worse at K=24, test K=16 to see whether flexible budget allocation helps more at tighter sparsity.","If `batch_topk` clearly loses at K=24, reject this support-allocation branch and move to another fundamentally different family such as `residual_vq` rather than any scalar sweep.","If `batch_topk` wins at K=24, follow with K=16 or K=32 to map whether the gain generalizes across the mid-K band."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/13_20260326_175854/round_summaries/round_0065.json:29:        "key": "ARCHITECTURE",
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0225.json:19:    "hypothesis": "\u5019\u9009 family: jumprelu\u3002\u6700\u7ec8\u91cd\u6784\u516c\u5f0f\u4e3a x_hat = \u03a3_i \u03b1_i b_i\uff0c\u5176\u4e2d {b_i} \u6765\u81ea\u5355\u4e2a\u9759\u6001\u5411\u91cf\u5e93\uff1bJumpReLU \u53ea\u6539\u53d8\u5355\u6837\u672c\u5728\u7ebf\u4fa7\u7684\u9608\u503c\u5316\u652f\u6301\u5f62\u6210\u4e0e\u7cfb\u6570\u8ba1\u7b97\uff0c\u4e0d\u6539\u53d8 decoder \u7aef\u7684\u5355\u5e93\u6709\u9650\u52a0\u6743\u548c\u5f62\u5f0f\uff0c\u56e0\u6b64\u53ef\u76f4\u63a5\u5bfc\u51fa\u5230 LUTurbo/Lottable \u7684\u201c\u67e5\u8868 + \u52a0\u6743\u6c42\u548c + \u9009\u62e9\u6027\u8865\u507f\u201d\u63a8\u7406\u94fe\u8def\uff0c\u517c\u5bb9\u6027\u5224\u65ad\u4e3a\u76f4\u63a5\u517c\u5bb9\u3002r223 \u5df2\u786e\u8ba4 `topk@EF1,K248` \u7684\u5411\u4e0a LR \u5206\u652f\u6ca1\u6709\u6536\u76ca\uff0cr224 \u4e5f\u786e\u8ba4 lowrank_factorized_residual \u7684 scorer \u538b\u7f29\u5728 <0.5x \u76ee\u6807\u533a\u4ecd\u843d\u540e\u4e8e\u540c\u6210\u672c topk\uff1b\u56e0\u6b64\u5f53\u524d\u6700\u6709\u4fe1\u606f\u91cf\u7684\u4e0b\u4e00\u6b65\uff0c\u4e0d\u662f\u7ee7\u7eed\u6e05\u6d17\u5df2\u9971\u548c family \u7684 recipe\uff0c\u800c\u662f\u5728\u4e0d\u589e\u52a0 total_cost \u7684\u524d\u63d0\u4e0b\u6d4b\u8bd5\u65b0\u7684\u540c\u6210\u672c selector \u673a\u5236\u3002\u4e25\u683c\u951a\u5b9a r222\uff0c\u53ea\u6539\u4e00\u4e2a env \u53c2\u6570 `ARCHITECTURE=jumprelu`\uff0c\u4fdd\u7559 `EF=1,K=248,signum,LR=3.0e-3,AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` \u4e0d\u53d8\uff0c\u9a8c\u8bc1 learned-threshold \u652f\u6301\u5851\u5f62\u80fd\u5426\u5728\u76f8\u540c `total_cost\u22480.49x` \u4e0b\uff0c\u628a <0.5x \u533a\u57df FVU \u538b\u5230\u5f53\u524d topk \u6700\u4f73 0.1462 \u4ee5\u4e0b\uff0c\u6216\u8005\u81f3\u5c11\u7ed9\u51fa\u6bd4 topk \u66f4\u6709\u5e0c\u671b\u7684\u66f2\u7ebf\u5f62\u72b6\u800c\u4e0d\u62d6\u6162\u8bad\u7ec3\u3002",
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0225.json:25:    "self_review": "\u8be5\u63d0\u6848\u4e25\u683c\u9075\u5b88\u5355\u53d8\u91cf\u539f\u5219\uff1a\u76f8\u5bf9\u6709\u6548\u53c2\u8003\u8f6e r222 \u53ea\u6539 `ARCHITECTURE` \u4e00\u4e2a env \u53c2\u6570\uff0cK\u3001EF\u3001optimizer\u3001LR\u3001AUXK_ALPHA \u548c\u6240\u6709\u8fd0\u884c\u65f6\u53c2\u6570\u5168\u90e8\u4fdd\u6301\u4e0d\u53d8\u3002\u9009\u62e9 `jumprelu` \u800c\u4e0d\u662f\u7ee7\u7eed\u56de\u5230 topk/group_topk\uff0c\u662f\u56e0\u4e3a\u5b83\u5728\u5386\u53f2\u4e0a\u867d\u672a\u6210\u4e3a\u4e3b\u7ebf\uff0c\u4f46\u6bd4\u7eaf grouped \u7ade\u4e89\u66f4\u63a5\u8fd1\u201c\u540c\u6210\u672c\u4e0b\u6539\u53d8\u652f\u6301\u5851\u5f62\u201d\u7684\u72ec\u7acb\u95ee\u9898\uff0c\u540c\u65f6\u4e0d\u4f1a\u989d\u5916\u62ac\u9ad8\u90e8\u7f72\u6216\u9009\u62e9\u6210\u672c\u3002",
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0225.json:29:        "key": "ARCHITECTURE",
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0225.json:63:    "self_review": "\u8be5\u63d0\u6848\u4e25\u683c\u9075\u5b88\u5355\u53d8\u91cf\u539f\u5219\uff1a\u76f8\u5bf9\u6709\u6548\u53c2\u8003\u8f6e r222 \u53ea\u6539 `ARCHITECTURE` \u4e00\u4e2a env \u53c2\u6570\uff0cK\u3001EF\u3001optimizer\u3001LR\u3001AUXK_ALPHA \u548c\u6240\u6709\u8fd0\u884c\u65f6\u53c2\u6570\u5168\u90e8\u4fdd\u6301\u4e0d\u53d8\u3002\u9009\u62e9 `jumprelu` \u800c\u4e0d\u662f\u7ee7\u7eed\u56de\u5230 topk/group_topk\uff0c\u662f\u56e0\u4e3a\u5b83\u5728\u5386\u53f2\u4e0a\u867d\u672a\u6210\u4e3a\u4e3b\u7ebf\uff0c\u4f46\u6bd4\u7eaf grouped \u7ade\u4e89\u66f4\u63a5\u8fd1\u201c\u540c\u6210\u672c\u4e0b\u6539\u53d8\u652f\u6301\u5851\u5f62\u201d\u7684\u72ec\u7acb\u95ee\u9898\uff0c\u540c\u65f6\u4e0d\u4f1a\u989d\u5916\u62ac\u9ad8\u90e8\u7f72\u6216\u9009\u62e9\u6210\u672c\u3002",
